 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ubanegrivm.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Banegrivm</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 254<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(10/22/01 4:57:29 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=66.topic&index=20>Reply</a>    <br>Community Supporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Guilds?</span><hr size=1> I don't think it would be that bad, plus I do think it would be a counter to ubers and d00ds because then they would be forced to actually leading, instead of just doing raids and what not and not taking responsibility for its memberships actions.<br>
<br>
Why do I say all this? The old Neverwinter Nights game from AOL was very much like this. It was incredible. It made all the guilds so colorfull. Guild Leaders were held accountable for their members and took responsibility for any misgivings done or what not. <br>
<br>
There were sanctioned and non sanctioned guilds and also limited space to make guilds. Hence there were not 50 guilds running around, and everything had a rich flavor to it. <p>Banegrivm Shadowblight<br>Sovereign Lord of the 1st Fist of Light<br>www.1stfistoflight.com</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ucloudien.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Cloudien</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 45<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(10/22/01 7:12:04 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=66.topic&index=21>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Guilds?</span><hr size=1> I'd have to agree with some of what Kal has to say, even though it was put... how can I say it... with the grace and tact of a gnoll <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
Or should I say troll?  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :lol --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/laugh.gif ALT=":lol"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
<br>
A couple of days ago I got a tell out of the blue:<br>
&quot;Would u like to join our guild?&quot;<br>
(I said no for the reasons below. He wouldn't take &quot;no&quot; for an answer though, so I eventually had to stay silent)<br>
<br>
*Shudder*  Several uh... conflicts of personalities and interests here:<br>
1) If I were to join a guild, it'd be because they want me for *me*, not my ability to sit in a chatroom and type #guildapprove<br>
2) It'd be a guild that at least try to make an effort to roleplay, even if it's just some of the time.  But at least half-decent attempts at first contact.  I mean... &quot;u&quot;?  *Shudder*<br>
3) Picking up people by saying &quot;want to join our guild?&quot; and not even getting to know them is a bad idea.  I know it's tough getting 10 members... but I'd rather have a leader who puts that extra effort in, rather than risking picking up any kind of... trash... just to get started.<br>
4) I don't like being harassed or begged, and my prospective guild leader was practically doing both.  Not a good start, if that's how it's to continue!<br>
<br>
Chances are, if I do join a guild (or start one if I feel up to the commitment), it'll be one of regular hunting friends I've met and enjoyed the company of.<br>
<br>
Golsec <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ucloudien.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Cloudien</A> at: 10/22/01 7:14:26 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ucandamar.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Candamar</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 7<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(10/22/01 8:27:27 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=66.topic&index=22>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Guilds?</span><hr size=1> I have to agree as well. In the past, I have fallen for a few 'guild advertisements', and they ended up being bad experiences where I quietly guild-removed after a few days.  For me, the only way now to consider a guild is to adventure with its members, get to know them and how they fight, interact with each other,etc.  That is the way it was for me on M-T, finally - a guild you are selected to, rather than one that is a free for all, to me denotes organization, clear purpose, and general strength.  It is also a guild you want to contribute to, after going through the process of screening/selection  That is one rigorous process I do not regret in the slightest, for it provided me with the best of my EQ times.<br>
<br>
That's just my take on things...a successful guild has selective membership, to weed out the folks that don't fit in with the rest.  I've seen too many guilds break apart due to poor membership decisions that led to reputation issues and general mayhem, and that is always an ugly thing.<br>
<br>
Just my take on things, and I've had some rum this eve, so I apologize if there is a garbled train of thought.  Have a good eve!<br>
<br>
<br>
PS And Liusadh, I thought I recognized you from somewhere but couldn't place it, and now I can...go M-T, let the roleplayers find their home at last!<br>
